# One Component Per File

Each `.tsx` file should export **only one React component**. This includes skeleton components, loading states, and error states.

## Structure

```
my-component/
├── my-component.tsx           # Main component
├── my-component-skeleton.tsx  # Skeleton/loading state
├── my-component-error.tsx     # Error state (if needed)
├── styles.ts                  # Shared styled components
└── index.ts                   # Re-exports (optional)
```

## Examples

```tsx
// ✅ Good: Separate files
// my-component.tsx
export const MyComponent = () => { ... }

// my-component-skeleton.tsx
export const MyComponentSkeleton = () => { ... }

// ❌ Bad: Multiple components in one file
export const MyComponent = () => { ... }
const MyComponentSkeleton = () => { ... }  // Should be in separate file
```

## Exceptions

- **Styled components** can remain in the same file if they're only used by that component
- **Shared styled components** used by multiple files should go in `styles.ts`
- **Small helper components** (< 10 lines) that are only used within the file can stay inline

## Benefits

- Clear file responsibility
- Easier code navigation
- Better tree-shaking
- Simpler imports
- Cleaner git diffs
